channel.title: Corfu 2010
channel.description:
We stayed an a small hotel on the top of the hill of the Komeno peninsula, just north of Corfu town, where breakfast was usually ample (if plagued by wasps), the pool was refreshing, and the shady garden was a tranquil spot for a bit of reading.
Close by were good beaches for snorkeling (remember to empty your pockets first - cameras don’t like getting wet - it’s a miracle we still managed to get these photos off the memory card...oops).
Tip: If you hire a quad bike for going up a mountain make sure its got at least 100cc unless you want to do a Fred Flintstone impression on the way up.
Those clever Venetians planted the whole island with olive trees, so its nice and green and shady, unlike the islands close to Turkey, which are more rocky and barren. They also refortified the original castle, then built another bigger one also in the town. Later on the Brits held the protectorate, and Kaiser Wilhelm lived there for a bit too. Apparently this results in a mixture of architectural and cultural influences. Indeed there is a cricket pitch in the Esplanade park, a carpet wicket at least... but the boundary is very very short and surrounded by a car park on several sides. Hitting a 6 would be rather easy and probably cause some unrest amongst local drivers.
Eating out was nearly always very very good, the highlight being stopping for lunch in a small family run eatery in Corfu town. Other than the ubiquitous wasp hazard, eating was a delight. Cheese!
